Biographies of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang

The Tingwei Zhang Shizhi was a man of Duyang, his courtesy name being Ji. He had an older brother Zhong with whom he lived. Using his property, he became a Cavalry Lang, serving Emperor Xiaowen. For ten years he could not be transferred, and he had no reputation. Shizhi said, "Being an official for a long time diminishes Zhong's property, and I am not successful." He wanted to resign and return home. The Zhonglang Jiang Yuan Ang knew his worth and regretted his departure, so he requested to transfer Shizhi to fill the post of Yezhe. After Shizhi had finished his audience, he took the opportunity to speak of matters of advantage. Emperor Wen said, "Lower it, do not have overly high discussions, make it so that it can be implemented today." Thereupon, Shizhi spoke of the affairs between Qin and Han, and for a long time about the reasons why Qin lost and Han rose. Emperor Wen praised it, and thus appointed Shizhi as Yezhe Puye.

Shizhi followed on a tour and ascended the tiger enclosure. The Emperor asked the Shanglin Wei about the registers of the various birds and beasts; after more than ten questions, the Wei looked left and right, completely unable to answer. The Hujuan Sefu from the side answered on behalf of the Wei the Emperor's questions about the registers of birds and beasts very thoroughly, wishing to show his ability to respond orally with endless echoes. Emperor Wen said, "Should not an official be like this? The Wei is incompetent!" He then decreed Shizhi to appoint the Sefu as Shanglin Ling. Shizhi stepped forward after a long time and said, "Your Majesty, what kind of person do you consider Jianghou Zhou Bo?" The Emperor said, "An elder." He asked again, "What kind of person is Dongyanghou Zhang Xiangru?" The Emperor again said, "An elder." Shizhi said, "Jianghou and Dongyanghou are called elders, yet these two men, when speaking of affairs, could not even get the words out of their mouths. How could they imitate this Sefu's talkative, sharp mouth and quick replies! Moreover, Qin employed officials of the pen, and the officials competed to outdo each other in urgent, harsh scrutiny, but their flaw was merely superficial formality, lacking the reality of compassion. For this reason, their faults were not heard, and it declined until the Second Emperor, when the empire crumbled. Now, Your Majesty, because of the Sefu's eloquence, promotes him exceptionally; I fear the empire will follow this trend, competing in eloquence without substance. Moreover, those below are influenced by those above faster than an echo responds to a sound; your actions cannot but be examined carefully." Emperor Wen said, "Good." He then stopped and did not appoint the Sefu.

The Emperor got into his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, and proceeded slowly, asking Shizhi about the flaws of Qin. Shizhi answered fully and plainly. Upon reaching the palace, the Emperor appointed Shizhi as Gongche Ling.

Shortly after, the Crown Prince and Liangwang rode together in a carriage to court and did not dismount at the Sima Gate. Thereupon, Shizhi pursued and stopped the Crown Prince and Liangwang from entering the palace gate. He then impeached them for not dismounting at the public gate, which was disrespectful, and memorialized it. When Bo Taihou heard of this, Emperor Wen took off his hat and apologized, saying, "I was not careful in teaching my sons." Bo Taihou then sent an envoy with a decree to pardon the Crown Prince and Liangwang, and only then were they allowed to enter. Emperor Wen therefore considered Shizhi extraordinary and appointed him as Zhongdafu.

Shortly after, he became Zhonglang Jiang. He followed on a tour to Baling, and they stood on the north looking down at the edge. At this time, Shen Furen was accompanying them. The Emperor pointed out the Xinfeng road to Shen Furen, saying, "This leads to the Handan road." He had Shen Furen play the se, and the Emperor himself sang leaning on the se, his thoughts sorrowful and mournful. He looked back and said to the ministers, "Alas! If one uses the stones of the North Mountain for the outer coffin, uses chopped ramie and silk floss to fill it, and lacquers the spaces, how could it be moved!" The attendants all said, "Good." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is something desirable inside, even if it is sealed in the South Mountain, there will still be cracks; if there is nothing desirable inside, even without a stone outer coffin, what is there to worry about!" Emperor Wen praised this. Later, he appointed Shizhi as Tingwei.

Shortly after, the Emperor went out and crossed the Zhongwei Bridge. A man ran out from under the bridge, startling the horses of the imperial carriage. Thereupon, he sent cavalry to arrest him and handed him over to the Tingwei. Shizhi interrogated him. The man said, "I am a man from the county, I heard the clearing of the road, and hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, I came out, saw the imperial carriage and riders, and just ran." The Tingwei submitted his verdict: one man violated the clearing of the road, the punishment should be a fine. Emperor Wen was angry and said, "This man personally startled my horses; my horses are fortunately gentle, but if they were other horses, would they not have thrown and injured me? Yet the Tingwei only sentences him to a fine!" Shizhi said, "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. Now the law is like this, but to change it and make it heavier means the law will not be trusted by the people. Moreover, at that time, if Your Majesty had ordered him executed on the spot, it would have been done. Now that it has been handed down to the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the balance of the world; if it tilts once, the application of the law throughout the world will become light or heavy, where shall the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long while, the Emperor said, "The Tingwei's verdict is correct."

